explanation:
Photo-electric effect is the phenomenon of emission of electrons from the surface of metals, when light radiations of suitable frequency fall on them. When a radiation of frequency {tex}
u{/tex} is incident on a metal surface, it is absorbed in the form of discrete photons each of energy {tex}h
u{/tex} . Photoelectric emission occurs because of single collision of a photon with a free electron. The energy of the photon is used to free the electron from the metal surface. It is equal to the work function W 0 of the metal. provide kinetic energy to the emitted Electron. {tex}	herefore \quad h v=K_{\max }+W_{0}{/tex} or {tex}K_{\max }= rac{1}{2} m v_{\max }^{2}=h v-W_{0}{/tex} This is Einstein&#39;s photoelectric equation. Clearly, above the threshold frequency {tex}
u_0{/tex} , K max {tex}\propto{/tex} {tex}
u{/tex} i.e., the maximum K.E. of the emitted electrons depends linearly on the frequency of incident radiation. When v < v 0 , K max becomes negative. The kinetic energy becomes negative which has no physical meaning. Hence there is no photoelectric emission below the threshold frequency v 0 . It is obvious from the photo-electric equation that the maximum K.E. of photo-electrons does not depend on the intensity of incident light.

